	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_144152">
	
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_144152"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				If your viewpoint changes as you get older, is it because you are finally seeing the &quot;truth&quot; as you get older, or is it because your entire notion of how the government should work was subjective to begin with and you're just changing your view to fit your new circumstances?
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
It really has nothing to do with “truth,” and more what you said next.  Basically, one you are young your idealism has no “cost.”  Sure, you know on an abstract level that people pay taxes, but it isn’t something that really affects you personally.  Idealistically, who could be against feeding the poor, curing the sick, etc.?  <br />
<br />
Well, when you get older, and if you join the working/middle class, your “idealism” begins to have a cost.  Suddenly, you have a home, a car payment, kids, education, utilities, etc.  So when you make $40,000/year, and take home $25,000, it stings.  You start to think, “If I had that $15,000 the Government took from me, I would not be struggling so hard.”   <br />
<br />
And then you begin to ask yourself why you should be paying for other people, particularly if they are not working, or are not working as hard.  If I am working so hard, why can’t they?  Mostly, when it is YOUR money that is being taken, it the cost becomes personal and idealism becomes abstract.  <br />
<br />
Taxes are all about “Interests” and “factions.”  People who receive benefits from other people’s money want to keep those benefits.  People who pay, but do not receive the bulk of the benefits, don’t want to pay as much.  The issue really is that simple at its most crass level of analysis.  It IS a matter of perspective.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
